                    <msContents>
                        <summary>
                            <seg type="para">
                                This fragment consists of a single folio, probably extracted from the binding of a Latin manuscript codex. One side, now the verso,
                                contains several Greek texts: two epigrams (the first attributed to Posidippus of Pella, the second Metrodorus' reply),
                                the two <title>Antistoicheiae by Maximus Planudes</title>, followed by an extract from the sayings of the Seven Sages.
                                The other side, now the recto, contains some psalms in Latin. The outer third has a slip of another leaf of the same manuscript,
                            stuck on it upside down. </seg> 
                            <seg type="para">The fragment was acquired by Constantin von Tischendorf 
                                and bought from his heirs by Cambridge University Library in 1876.</seg>
                            <seg type="para">Dr Matteo Di Franco</seg>
                        </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="grc" otherLangs="la">Greek and Latin</textLang>

