                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" xml:id="hand-1">
                                <p>The Latin text is written by an Italian hand of the 15th century.</p>
                            </handNote>
                            
                            <handNote scope="major" xml:id="hand-2">
                                <p>The Greek text was copied in a small-format cursive-like <term type="script">mixed minuscule</term> 
                                    script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown and red ink.
                                    It does not show any marked variation in letter size, but for 
                                    <hi rend="italic">beta</hi>, present in the bilobate and modern forms,
                                    and <hi rend="italic">epsilon</hi>.
                                    <hi rend="italic">Delta</hi> is outlined in two strokes, elongated upwards, ending with a cap.  
                                    Breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or breathings, but 
                                    the circumflex is traced in a single gesture together with the <hi rend="italic">ypsilon</hi> 
                                    or <hi rend="italic">omega</hi>.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="colInit">Four enlarged initials in red ink in uncial majuscule.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>

